post_text: Today marks the district's official farewell to Dr. Maryellen Brunelle, APS Superintendent. During her 12 year tenure as Auburn's educational leader, she has been a mentor, colleague, and friend to all within the Auburn community. It is only fitting that we close with a quote from her to mark the end of her time with us - "It is all good!" Indeed, Maryellen, "it is all good" and we thank you for your tireless efforts on behalf of the town's children. All of us will continue to "see the glass half full" no matter the circumstance. We wish you the best in retirement and hope you visit often!

post_text: Tomorrow, April 27, 2011, marks the 9 year anniversary of the death of Major David Brodeur in Kabul, Afghanistan. I am proud to announce, Aaron Pigeon, AHS Class of 2020, has been selected to attend the United States Air Force Academy in Colorado Springs, Colorado. Aaron is the first graduate selected for the Air Force Academy since David. We are immensely proud of both David and Aaron. Having known David and his family my entire life, Aaron embodies EVERYTHING David stood for in life and death. We celebrate both David and Aaron for their incredible sacrifices and accomplishments on behalf of a grateful community, state, and nation.

Swanson Road Community Service Learning Projects for the Week of April 13-17, 2020

1. Random Acts of Kindness/Spreading Positivity:

Spread kindness, brighten someone’s day…Leave positive messages in your driveway, on the curb, at the park, on someone’s doorstep, or around your neighborhood in the form of sidewalk chalk messages, painted rocks, written notes or any creative way you can think of!

2. Create a Coupon Book:

Create a Helpful Things I Can Do Coupon Book with 5-10 coupons of chores and acts of kindness you can do around the house and then give it to your parents/guardians

*** Remember to join your grade level School-Wide Projects Google Classroom to submit pictures and/or a written summary of your work to earn a certificate of completion. ***

post_text:
SWIS Community Service Learning Projects

Week of: April 6 – 10, 2020

Neighborhood “Bear Hunt”/Scavenger Hunt

Background Info: Teddy bears are appearing everywhere along streets made empty by coronavirus.

And they're fair game for bored kids turned friendly 'hunters.'

The stuffed animals are appearing in windows around the world in global "Teddy Bear Hunts" for children — uniting neighborhoods and giving children an exciting, social-distancing-safe scavenger hunt activity during coronavirus lock downs.

CHALLENGE #1:

Place a teddy bear (or any stuffed animal) in the window.
Read/Watch: Michael Rosen’s Were Going On A Bear Hunt https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0gyI6ykDwds
Head out on a beautiful day and start searching your neighborhood for bears!
*Bonus/Extension Activity: Take a younger sibling with you as you walk and hunt, or jump in the car with the family to search the whole town.

***CHALLENGE #2
Create Cards for Hospitalized Children

http://www.cardsforhospitalizedkids.com/

post_text:
National Junior Honor Society Organization is the nation's premier organization established to recognize outstanding middle school students. More than just an honor roll, NJHS
serves to honor those students who have demonstrated excellence in the areas of scholarship, leadership, service, citizenship and character.

A cumulative average of 90% in all subjects for 4 Trimesters.

Seventh Grade Students: all 3 Trimesters of sixth grade and the first Trimester of seventh grade.

Eighth Grade Students: all 3 Trimesters of seventh grade and the first Trimester of eighth grade.

Students must demonstrate qualities of leadership, character, service, and community outreach.

Congratulations to all of Auburn Middle School's newly inducted members.

shared_text:
Auburn Public School District added 5 new photos.
December 17, 2019 at 10:59 AM ·

The word of the month for December at Auburn Middle School is “empathy.” Empathy is generally defined as the ability to sense and feel other people's emotions. In the last few weeks, our AMS students have proven time and time again that they are not only empathetic, but also caring, generous, and thoughtful. The annual Student Council toy drive to benefit Auburn Youth and Family services was a tremendous success thanks to the help of our students, their families, and our staff.

We exceeded our expectations with over 300 gifts donated.

While we wish that we lived in a world where everyone had what they want and need in life, the reality is that we don’t. It fills our hearts to know that we will be making a difference in a child’s life even if for just one day. We hope that the real reason for the season has been sparked in all of our students. #dogoodthings #payitforwardams

Wishing you all a safe and happy holiday season.

post_text: The APS TEACHERS versus AHS UNIFIED BASKETBALL TEAM will take place on Thursday, November 21st at AHS, tip-off is at 6:00 p.m.Don't be late! Please come support the APS community while contributing to a great cause, watching what promises to be a great competition and cheer on our Unified Basketball Players and staff from each building in the DIstrict. Entrance fee is $5 for adults, $3 for students, with kids under five and senior citizens get in for free. Enter to win some raffle baskets which include, make your own slime kits, gift cards and even a scratch ticket tree! All monies collected will support our Unified School Day Games in May and the Special Olympics Polar Plunge. Come and celebrate our Unified School District and the AHS Unified Basketball Team! WE CHOOSE TO INCLUDE!

post_text: As you might be aware, from our October 24th post, Auburn High School closed its annual Homecoming Spirit Week by launching Auburn 365Z - A program focused on doing acts of kindness 365 days a year. Mr. Paul Ford, a founding member of 365Z (http://www.365z.org/ ), his daughter Brittany, and board members Tim and Catherine Fontaine were present to help kick off the Auburn Chapter. You can watch our video here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9qji3LbgiFQ. Our first act of kindness is supporting our veterans here and abroad. Students by grade and Homebase have been asked to focus on the listed items below. We will take items until December 6th and then deliver them. Community members, parents, and anyone else who would like to donate may bring items to the main office. Students should drop items off to their Homebase teachers. Thank you for helping us help them 🇺🇸 !
